1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,042
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sammasambuddhassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sammasambuddhassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sammasambuddhassam

2
00:00:29,443 --> 00:00:33,152
Homage to the blessed noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,218 --> 00:00:50,067
So, yesterday we did the hindrances, how to deal with those states of mind which take us away from the object.

4
00:00:52,984 --> 00:01:20,123
even though they're called hindrances they are our teachers aren't they because they're there to tell us what's wrong with us and through our instructions we can deal with them in a skillful way so we have to look upon them as welcome enemies something like that we have to open our hearts to our hindrances

5
00:01:23,512 --> 00:01:29,118
Now, there's the other side of the equation, which is the seven factors of enlightenment and the five spiritual faculties.

6
00:01:30,079 --> 00:01:32,141
And I'm going to try and dovetail them.

7
00:01:32,942 --> 00:01:36,808
And by the end of the talk, you'll be utterly confused.

8
00:01:38,810 --> 00:01:43,415
But I'll try and reduce it to a very simple statement at the end.

9
00:01:43,456 --> 00:01:51,105
And the best thing is, especially for those who don't know what I'm talking about, is to let it go in one ear and out the other.

10
00:01:52,739 --> 00:02:04,301
Because it's more in the sense of giving a certain confidence and a certain background knowledge which gives you faith, confidence in the process.

11
00:02:06,504 --> 00:02:14,781
And the ground of spiritual practice in terms of advancement is faith, faith.

12
00:02:16,229 --> 00:02:19,614
I was going to say sila, right conduct.

13
00:02:20,294 --> 00:02:23,400
Of course we always talk about sila and paññā.

14
00:02:23,980 --> 00:02:30,651
So paññā is the wisdom factor and sila refers to the conduct and the one must be mirrored in the other.

15
00:02:32,615 --> 00:02:40,347
But here we're talking more specifically about developing this quality of intuitive insight.

16
00:02:42,401 --> 00:02:50,248
So faith is crucial and the first thing is not to confuse that with belief.

17
00:02:50,269 --> 00:03:03,580
So if we define belief as faith in a statement such as I believe in a god or I don't believe in a god then that's not what the Buddha is talking about when he talks about saddha, faith.

18
00:03:03,600 --> 00:03:10,366
What he's talking about is a sense of confidence, a sense of trust.

19
00:03:10,347 --> 00:03:31,866
and if you think about it anytime you act especially those times during our lives when it's a big decision such as moving house or getting a job elsewhere or forming a relationship or going to live with somebody, marry them all those sorts of relationships

20
00:03:31,846 --> 00:03:58,038
all those sorts of occasions demand faith that you trust you trust in your own decision you trust in the way that you see things that you understand things and that there's something in the heart which is telling you that this is what you have to do otherwise you just wouldn't do it so you can see that the relationship between trust and commitment is crucial

21
00:03:58,019 --> 00:03:59,920
If you don't trust, you just don't do it.

22
00:04:00,521 --> 00:04:11,275
If you go to a surgeon to have the pimple removed at the end of your nose and you don't feel right about him or her, then you don't do it, you go and find somebody else.

23
00:04:15,038 --> 00:04:17,963
So that faith has two qualities.

24
00:04:18,103 --> 00:04:27,334
It has the qualities of understanding and the quality of trust which sort of comes more from the heart.

25
00:04:29,406 --> 00:04:36,839
So this understanding is got merely by listening to Dharma talks, reading.

26
00:04:38,101 --> 00:04:40,024
That's the first sort of understanding we have.

27
00:04:40,925 --> 00:04:43,730
It's a given and it makes sort of sense.

28
00:04:45,173 --> 00:04:52,004
The deeper understanding comes when that becomes our own way, that we've worked it out for ourselves.

29
00:04:52,541 --> 00:05:17,740
So you might hear somebody, for instance, explain the wheel of dependence origination, this psychology the Buddha taught, and it might initially make sense, but then when you reflect on it, it may begin to make more sense, and you can see that with that more sense there grows that sense of trust, that sort of coming from the heart, that willingness to investigate further.

30
00:05:19,762 --> 00:05:33,584
And of course through the practice of vipassana, what was an intellectual understanding then becomes a direct understanding, and that of course begins to cement the faith, begins to cement it.

31
00:05:36,603 --> 00:06:03,149
and it is said that faith doesn't become unshakeable until we've intuited nibbana so once a person has experienced nibbana then there's no way that that faith can be shaken because now they know for themselves absolutely that the teaching of the Buddha is true so it's not a matter then of losing faith anymore and in fact the Buddha gives it a different word

32
00:06:03,129 --> 00:06:12,783
For one word it's called an indriya, which is a faculty, and when somebody has an insight into Nibbāna it becomes a bāla, it becomes a strength, unshakable.

33
00:06:16,410 --> 00:06:26,024
And the quality of that understanding, the process, is really just that deepening of understanding, and it has this effect of trust.

34
00:06:26,685 --> 00:06:29,369
Now that trust is coming from the heart, isn't it?

35
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:31,973
It's something more, slightly more intuitive.

36
00:06:31,952 --> 00:06:42,271
So there are those people who need to understand the nth degree of the teaching before they dare to trust it.

37
00:06:43,211 --> 00:06:50,163
And there are those people who don't need much understanding, they just trust the feeling they have towards it.

38
00:06:50,144 --> 00:07:06,954
a particular teaching or towards a particular teacher and that's enough for them you see that feeling of an intuitive intuitive feeling that this is right for them most of us of course have to balance the two of them in some sort of proportion

39
00:07:07,778 --> 00:07:11,944
But you can understand that there are some people who just have faith.

40
00:07:12,564 --> 00:07:14,208
They just have faith.

41
00:07:14,228 --> 00:07:22,882
And you can diminish it by calling it blind faith because they can't draw up the arguments.

42
00:07:23,903 --> 00:07:31,574
But it can be just as deeply felt, just as deeply committed as the faith of somebody who can argue their point.

43
00:07:33,512 --> 00:07:41,326
And it was often a criticism that somebody had blind faith.

44
00:07:42,548 --> 00:07:47,757
But if your blind faith is actually in the truth, that's good, isn't it?

45
00:07:49,730 --> 00:07:56,516
I mean, if it actually turns out that what you've got blind faith in is the absolute truth, it saves you a lot of reading for a start.

46
00:07:57,997 --> 00:07:59,360
I mean, you just get on with the practice.

47
00:08:00,079 --> 00:08:14,995
So this movement of the heart towards faith, you see, is there at the beginning of our practice, and it supports everything that we're doing.

48
00:08:14,975 --> 00:08:22,869
And there's a lovely image given, I can't remember whether it came from the scriptures, but definitely it's in the Malindi Panya.

49
00:08:23,509 --> 00:08:33,388
So the Malindi Panya were questions and answers given by Nagasena, who was understood to be fully awakened.

50
00:08:33,368 --> 00:08:58,988
some centuries after the Buddha when all the north part of that world was all Greek because Alexander had conquered it so Malindi is actually the Greek king Maninda who would have been around Afghanistan and there he talks about the water purifying gem of the world conquering monarch

51
00:08:59,659 --> 00:09:03,125
In the scriptures you get this myth of the world-conquering monarch.

52
00:09:03,205 --> 00:09:16,585
Those of you who know the story of the Buddha, when he was seen by the wise man, he prophesied that this little baby would become either a world-conquering monarch or a fully self-enlightened being.

53
00:09:18,248 --> 00:09:24,957
And that's what made his father all upset and made sure that he brought him up to be a world-conquering monarch.

54
00:09:24,937 --> 00:09:25,940
That's the story.

55
00:09:26,880 --> 00:09:41,225
So this alter ego runs right through the scriptures that the Buddha could have become this and if he had he would have been this superb leader of the world bringing tremendous good conduct and all that.

56
00:09:41,206 --> 00:09:53,163
So, one of the gems that the person has, one of the things that they have to support that world-conquering manifestation is this water-purifying gem.

57
00:09:54,304 --> 00:10:08,765
So that when all the horses and the camels and the bullock carts have passed over the river with all the men carrying their shields and swords, of course the water is all disturbed, but by dropping this lovely gem into the water, the whole thing just becomes utterly purified.

58
00:10:09,995 --> 00:10:11,738
And that's a lovely image for faith.

59
00:10:11,957 --> 00:10:19,389
Because remember, if you think about it, before you make a decision, there's confusion, isn't there?

60
00:10:19,409 --> 00:10:20,591
A sense of confusion.

61
00:10:20,652 --> 00:10:21,033
Shall I?

62
00:10:21,133 --> 00:10:21,714
Shall I not?

63
00:10:22,394 --> 00:10:23,677
There's lots of doubt about.

64
00:10:24,538 --> 00:10:26,542
You don't know whether you will or whether you won't.

65
00:10:27,363 --> 00:10:29,447
You make your lists for and against.

66
00:10:30,268 --> 00:10:33,413
And then suddenly you commit and the whole thing just disappears.

67
00:10:33,774 --> 00:10:34,634
Just like that.

68
00:10:35,357 --> 00:10:40,645
And the heart with all its troubles and its anxieties just gets completely purified.

69
00:10:41,047 --> 00:10:48,378
It just all vanishes and suddenly there's this lovely blossoming of joy in one's commitment.

70
00:10:48,398 --> 00:10:51,442
So it's a lovely image to have that faith.

71
00:10:53,261 --> 00:11:02,254
Now, that faith underpins this paññā, and paññā is this intuitive intelligence.

72
00:11:02,975 --> 00:11:10,586
So it's because we have confidence in this teaching, we have confidence in the practice, that we actually can even start looking.

73
00:11:12,148 --> 00:11:18,355
And that looking, that observing, brings about its own insights, which then strengthens the faith.

74
00:11:18,976 --> 00:11:22,442
And so they tumble over each other into pure awakening.

75
00:11:26,302 --> 00:11:43,400
Now that intuitive intelligence is expressed in the other form, the seven factors of enlightenment, as investigation of dharma, dhammavichya.

76
00:11:43,380 --> 00:11:59,163
And when the Buddha is talking about that, remember, if you read the discourse on it, it's basically beginning to look at things the way he saw things.

77
00:11:59,182 --> 00:12:06,874
So we have those three characteristics, transience, not self, and how we create unsatisfactions for ourselves.

78
00:12:06,854 --> 00:12:28,456
but also this business of deconstructing things all this business around the hindrances and also all this business around the factors of enlightenment so that's all to do with investigating the Dharma as he calls it and

79
00:12:30,378 --> 00:12:35,965
That Dharma is supported, that investigation is supported by equanimity.

80
00:12:36,826 --> 00:12:39,369
Equanimity is one of these funny words really.

81
00:12:41,370 --> 00:12:43,153
It's not the same as calmness.

82
00:12:45,917 --> 00:12:54,326
Equanimity I think is best described as a perfect receptivity.

83
00:12:55,927 --> 00:12:58,389
Now, there's nothing stopping you from receiving.

84
00:12:58,770 --> 00:13:04,318
There's no reaction to what's actually coming at you.

85
00:13:04,339 --> 00:13:13,412
So, if you liken it to a judge, we expect the judge not to get caught up in the funny little arguments of these lawyers.

86
00:13:15,333 --> 00:13:16,235
See, at the head level.

87
00:13:17,177 --> 00:13:23,065
And we don't expect them to get caught up in the anger and emotion of the crowd, baying for blood.

88
00:13:24,293 --> 00:13:49,895
so it's that business of being able to be dispassionate not caught up in and of course as soon as we lift ourselves into the position of the observer it arises naturally because to observe you have to allow whatever is to be observed to manifest and we lose that sense of equanimity

89
00:13:50,010 --> 00:13:55,581
As soon as we dropped into any reaction, wanting, not wanting.

90
00:13:57,105 --> 00:14:02,475
So that equanimity has to be there for the investigation to be clear.

91
00:14:04,339 --> 00:14:07,947
And for the investigation to be clear, the intelligence must be awakened.

92
00:14:08,727 --> 00:14:12,254
And we won't do that unless we have faith in the process.

93
00:14:17,044 --> 00:14:26,498
now supporting that you've got concentration which is balanced with effort with proper energy

94
00:14:27,490 --> 00:14:55,302
concentration again is one of those funny things because normally when you say to somebody you know get concentrated or be focused you expect this sort of real narrowing down sort of collapse into some sort of tightness you know but concentration in this sense just means being able to keep the attention on the object full stop

95
00:14:57,712 --> 00:15:06,850
And the effort which is to be developed is just the effort needed to keep the attention on the object.

96
00:15:08,153 --> 00:15:15,148
So if that concentration becomes tight, then you start moving into restlessness.

97
00:15:16,629 --> 00:15:19,873
it begins to shake, you see, and you can't keep your mind on it.

98
00:15:21,374 --> 00:15:26,298
And when that happens, the meditator has to recognize that, you see.

99
00:15:26,778 --> 00:15:46,096
So the restlessness, and this is where the meditation gets, shall we say, a little tricky, because you may be thinking that the restlessness is coming from something arising out of the heart or something, but actually it might be to do because you're trying too hard.

100
00:15:46,076 --> 00:16:11,427
trying to become too concentrated so that business of effort and concentration if you think of a camera when you focus it you know the old ones before they made these little machines where you had to actually use your fingers and if you think of that you see that's the effort and then there's the focus you see

101
00:16:14,157 --> 00:16:26,595
Now the other side of concentration, when you have too much concentration but not enough energy, is that of course the mind now is like a laser beam, it's facing one way.

102
00:16:26,634 --> 00:16:32,823
And if the energy is not there to support it, then you drop into a state of unconsciousness.

103
00:16:33,918 --> 00:16:58,947
that's not the same as sleep and you'll know the meditator knows when that's happened rather than sleep because the body remains upright because the energy is there alright the concentration is there but because the energy is not supporting it then it's as though the mind just stops as a blank count and you wake up and

104
00:16:58,927 --> 00:17:27,297
however depending on the power of that concentration it can last for various lengths of time there's a lovely story about a Hindu guru who was an adept at these very high jhanic absorption states and he gave an instruction to his attendant to get him some water and went to meditate and he went into one of these states

105
00:17:28,271 --> 00:17:36,323
Ten years later, he comes out of this state and his first words are, where's my water?

106
00:17:38,125 --> 00:17:41,269
And what it's meant, the tale is meant to symbolize that nothing happens.

107
00:17:41,289 --> 00:17:46,317
It's a complete waste of time getting into these constricted blank states.

108
00:17:47,577 --> 00:17:56,170
And it's funny how many people actually believe that meditation is about blanking the mind, about sort of turning it off and ending up in this dead place.

109
00:17:57,584 --> 00:18:11,069
so when that happens we can congratulate ourselves because the concentration is good but then we have to also recognize that the effort there's something wrong with the effort

110
00:18:13,143 --> 00:18:43,150
and normally when you look at it there's been a moment there where you've lost interest where something has lost its empowering of that looking and the whole thing drops when the concentration has become too tight then you have to look at your effort so the effort to gain the effort always to achieve and when that happens you have to really remind yourself that to be aware is the achievement that's it there's nothing else to achieve

111
00:18:43,130 --> 00:19:03,130
and once you sort of drum that into yourself it does stop you wanting to go beyond the present moment because whenever you want to achieve something it's always in the future isn't it when you've achieved it you've achieved it but while you're wanting to achieve it's not here it's over there so the mind is always moving ahead of itself

112
00:19:04,003 --> 00:19:33,318
So, if you find yourself, you know, when feeling restless, and you've got an inkling that it's not really to do, because the body feels good, and it feels light, and it's okay, but there's this restlessness, then, especially, not so much at the beginning of a week retreat, but maybe, you know, within two or three days, when you really settle, then just see if some idea of getting something has not crept in.

113
00:19:33,298 --> 00:19:44,607
again the story from the scriptures is of Nanda Nanda was the cousin of the Buddha

114
00:19:45,314 --> 00:20:11,372
and he was really practicing hard and getting nowhere and getting all this sort of restlessness and stuff and so he began to give up and he decided that what he would do in this lifetime was create good karma and then have another go in the next one so the Buddha having heard this or intuiting it appeared by his side and said Nanda what are you doing mate

115
00:20:12,330 --> 00:20:33,933
and he gave him the son he said no no he said what you've got to do is you've got to have this effort and he gave the image of tuning a lute can't remember the proper word for that instrument but it's a lute it's a stringed instrument and he said to get the right pitch

116
00:20:34,807 --> 00:20:38,679
It mustn't be too tight and it mustn't be too loose.

117
00:20:39,401 --> 00:20:41,105
Just getting the right pitch.

118
00:20:41,627 --> 00:20:48,446
And of course, Ananda in no length of time, having got the right pitch, became fully awakened.

119
00:20:51,768 --> 00:21:02,771
Usually these little stories are glossed in the commentary to say things like Ananda went off to the forest for 25 years and became fully enlightened.

120
00:21:02,791 --> 00:21:08,223
But actually in the scriptures it said he struggled with it and became fully awakened.

121
00:21:08,827 --> 00:21:16,760
So effort is a cheeky one for us because Western culture is about achieving.

122
00:21:16,780 --> 00:21:18,282
It's about achieving, about getting.

123
00:21:19,224 --> 00:21:26,917
And one of the problems of the Vipassana school is that it does put to us certain achievements.

124
00:21:27,317 --> 00:21:27,919
I mean, they're there.

125
00:21:27,979 --> 00:21:33,367
They're called the Vipassananyanas, the insights that come with Vipassana.

126
00:21:33,347 --> 00:21:45,588
And then there are four stages of sanctity for different stream entrants, once returner, non-returner, and then finally this adahat.

127
00:21:45,608 --> 00:21:56,587
And what that does for us, or the way we can look at it so that it doesn't become some sort of achievement, is again this feeling that the path is actually well delineated.

128
00:21:57,377 --> 00:22:03,111
It's not a sort of, we're not on a path which is sort of higgledy-piggledy and it may or may not.

129
00:22:03,131 --> 00:22:11,167
It's actually the path leading to breakthrough is very clearly marked.

130
00:22:11,528 --> 00:22:12,872
Very clearly marked.

131
00:22:12,852 --> 00:22:18,948
Having said that, the path of the Vipassana knowledge is not the only way.

132
00:22:19,388 --> 00:22:28,531
And people have achieved amazing insight very quickly, usually because of some great shock.

133
00:22:28,511 --> 00:22:36,042
Somebody's close has died or they've fallen off a bridge or something.

134
00:22:36,083 --> 00:22:43,753
Something happens which gives them a shock and it can really pull them out of a particular mind state and turn their lives.

135
00:22:44,575 --> 00:22:48,359
One of the more interesting ones is this near death experience that people have.

136
00:22:48,339 --> 00:23:03,413
So, it's not the, I wouldn't say it was the only delineated path, you do get slightly different ones in the Mahayana, but it's definitely well delineated in this particular context.

137
00:23:03,393 --> 00:23:31,964
school and the the whole point about the mahasis teaching was that it was meant to be a direct attack on this particular path it was meant to be uh none of this business about trying to get blissed out or you know having having having cups of tea when you want it was straight on and and and he he was very successful so um this business of effort and concentration you see

138
00:23:33,025 --> 00:23:59,521
the other and those effort by the way and all that comes up in faculties too for those of you who know these things the other combination is calmness and it's badly translated as joy much better translated as interest

139
00:24:00,598 --> 00:24:27,265
so now interest is a funny emotion it's the sort of philosophers wonder you know it's a sort of wanting to know but you can feel it sort of coming from the heart and just as an aside remember just ask yourself did you ever have any problem with concentration when you were interested in something so that's why because

140
00:24:27,835 --> 00:24:54,383
the force of our practice is to awaken the intelligence it seems to me much more beneficial to raise interest rather than to worry about concentration and I'm always amazed how that manifests even in animals this sort of wonder

141
00:24:54,936 --> 00:24:59,682
I was once in a lovely place up in Penang, Malaya.

142
00:25:00,884 --> 00:25:07,750
And there was a plantation up there and I was offered to stay up there at this house which was lived in occasionally.

143
00:25:08,971 --> 00:25:21,767
And it was a lovely evening so I took this table out onto the forecourt there wanting to sort of lift myself off the ground because of bugs and stuff, snakes.

144
00:25:21,787 --> 00:25:24,910
And I tied this...

145
00:25:25,480 --> 00:25:52,804
mosquito net to the tree above me and brought me cushions out and everything and a cup of coffee and I sat on this table looking out through the mosquito net to the setting sun and as it grew darker and darker I suddenly realised I was facing east

146
00:25:53,797 --> 00:25:56,260
I was a little disappointed.

147
00:25:58,905 --> 00:26:04,095
There were these two dogs that every evening would scamper, would chase each other.

148
00:26:04,134 --> 00:26:07,460
Two very good friends would chase each other madly around.

149
00:26:07,500 --> 00:26:18,960
And on this particular evening, the one that I was sat out there waiting for the sunset, one of these dogs was late.

150
00:26:19,327 --> 00:26:22,634
And the other one began to pine and cry a little.

151
00:26:23,516 --> 00:26:27,983
And when the dog finally turned up, to my amazement, he sort of ran up.

152
00:26:28,003 --> 00:26:33,113
And when he saw this table with this figure and this...

153
00:26:33,413 --> 00:26:34,536
He stood there and he went...

154
00:26:37,147 --> 00:26:41,316
You know, while the other dog was biting him and doing all sorts of deaf things.

155
00:26:41,336 --> 00:26:42,116
I thought, my goodness.

156
00:26:43,840 --> 00:26:50,913
What an amazing sort of intelligence.

157
00:26:50,933 --> 00:26:52,356
Yeah, I must have looked really silly.

158
00:26:52,958 --> 00:26:53,798
To a dog, anyway.

159
00:26:56,785 --> 00:26:57,807
So...

160
00:26:59,203 --> 00:27:18,663
well I can't remember why I went into that oh yes interest so this quality of wanting to know you see even here you see just walking down the street with all these cows and bullocks it's just amazing they just come towards you wanting to know you see

161
00:27:19,640 --> 00:27:48,684
so it's something that we find in all creatures so it's a case of awakening that within us and that wanting to know that wonder sometimes you have to sort of work at it a bit you know just to raise your energy towards interest and like all these things these are all conditioned all conditionings so the more you condition yourself to become interested the more interested you become

162
00:27:49,036 --> 00:28:05,289
and the more interested you become the more you practice with verve and with right commitment and the more you practice with verve and right commitment the more you see and the more you're delighted so the more interested you become

163
00:28:05,269 --> 00:28:14,826
So these things have a sort of internal motor and I would say that interest is a real sort of motivation.

164
00:28:15,366 --> 00:28:24,762
But sometimes you have to feed it, especially when those little nasty things come up like boredom which is the direct enemy of interest.

165
00:28:26,701 --> 00:28:35,048
So when that comes up, remember that boredom is what is to be observed and not to be conned by, you know, that you need distraction.

166
00:28:36,670 --> 00:28:45,377
There was a monk I knew who would go to his teacher and say, I've been watching this breath and I'm really bored.

167
00:28:47,199 --> 00:28:53,585
And the teacher said, well, why don't you try watching it down here in the stomach?

168
00:28:53,704 --> 00:28:56,708
So he went away and he came back and he said, I'm watching it and I'm really bored.

169
00:28:57,328 --> 00:29:01,756
